em, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1295–1320":"about 1295–1320","1295–1320":"1295–1320","1290–1322":"1290–1322","1315–1360":"1315–1360","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1273–1343":"1273–1343","1275–1304":"1275–1304","1275":"1275","1273":"1273","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1290":"1290","Abt 1295":"about 1295","1304":"1304","1315":"1315","1862":"1862","1322":"1322","1310":"1310","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","before 1295":"before 1295","1317":"1317","Acton, Cheshire, England":"Acton, Cheshire, England","Chipping Sodbury, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Chipping Sodbury, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Coton, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Wem, Shropshire, England":"Wem, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Acton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places, especially in Shropshire and adjacent counties, named Acton. Generally, these are from Old English <i>āc</i> ‘oak’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. In Ireland the surname has been established in Connacht since the 17th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":20,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Acton was born about 1295, in Acton, Cheshire, England, her father, Roger de Acton, was 24 and her mother, Matilda Maud d'Agilofinges, was 21. She married Alan de Cotton in 1310, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1320, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 26."},"et":{"Abt 1295–1320":"umbes 1295–1320","1295–1320":"1295–1320","1290–1322":"1290–1322","1315–1360":"1315–1360","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1273–1343":"1273–1343","1275–1304":"1275–1304","1275":"1275","1273":"1273","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1290":"1290","Abt 1295":"umbes 1295","1304":"1304","1315":"1315","1862":"1862","1322":"1322","1310":"1310","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","before 12